frameDefinitions: An Agent manipulates a Sound_maker or a Cause causes the Sound_maker to emit a sound.
The words in this frame describe motion involving a Vehicle and someone who controls it, the Driver.
A Hunter tries to gain Food by way of outsmarting or tracking a living.
In this frame an Agriculturist cultivates Food.
A Grower endeavors to tend to and influence the environment of Food so as to foster its growth.
frameExamples: The monks would <t>ring</t> the bell until sundown.
Tim <t>drove</t> his car all the way across North America.
In the Congo, he hunted big game for the first time.
Peasants were encouraged to <t>cultivate</t> basic food crops such as beans and corn
listRoleDefinitions: The individual that manipulates a Sound_maker so that it makes Noise.
The entity that produces the Noise, as a result of the action of the Agent.
The inanimate force of nature that causes the <fen>Sound_maker</fen> to produce noise.
The time at which the noise is produced.
The location at which the sound is produced.
This is the being, typically human, that controls the <fen>Vehicle</fen> as it moves.
This is the means of conveyance controlled by the <fen>Driver</fen>.  It may move in any way or medium.  With verbs, <fen>Vehicle</fen> is usually expressed as Object:

Any expression which implies a definite starting-point of motion expresses the frame element <fen>Source</fen>. In prepositional phrases, the prepositional object expresses the starting point of motion.  With particles, the starting point of motion is understood from context.

Any description of a trajectory of motion which is neither a <fen>Source</fen> nor a <fen>Goal</fen> expresses the frame element <fen>Path</fen>. This includes directional expressions and 'middle of path'' expressions, e.g.:

Any expression which tells where the moving object(s) ends up as a result of the motion expresses the frame element <fen>Goal</fen>. Some particles imply the existence of a <fen>Goal</fen> which is understood in the context of utterance.

This frame element is used for expressions which describe a general area in which motion takes place when the motion is understood to be irregular and not to consist of a single linear path. Locative setting adjuncts of motion expressions may also be assigned this frame element.
The  <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Driver</fen> operates the <fen>Vehicle</fen>
The <fen>Place</fen> describes the location of a more specific motion (which has <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen>).
The <fen>Hunter</fen> is the agent hoping to obtain <fen>Food</fen>.
<fen>Food</fen> is the sought-out item by the <fen>Hunter</fen>.
This is the entity to which the <fen>Hunter</fen> pays attention. It is referred to as <fen>Ground</fen> because it serves as the background or context for the <fen>Food</fen>.
When the <fen>Time</fen> seeking action occurs.
The greater geographic location where the <fen>Hunter</fen> attempts to obtain <fen>Food</fen>.
The <fen>Agriculturist</fen> is the agent cultivating <fen>Food</fen>.
<fex name='Food'>Food</fex> is the item cultivated by the <fen>Agriculturist</fen>.
This is the the background or context for the <fen>Food</fen> to which the <fen>Agriculturist</fen> pays attention in his agricultural efforts.
When the agricultural event occurs.
The greater geographic location where the <fen>Agriculturist</fen> cultivates <fen>Food</fen>.
The <fen>Grower</fen> is the agent growing <fen>Food</fen>.

<fex name='Food'>Food</fex> is the item grown by the <fen>Grower</fen>, which can include things not traditionally eaten, like flowers, etc., or items for other consumption-related uses, like medicines, smokables, etc.
When the growing event occurs.
The greater geographic location where the <fen>Grower</fen> grows <fen>Food</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>You</fex> can ring the bell as often as you'd like.
The bikers rode <fex>all over the place</fex>.
<fex>Yesterday</fex>, Smithers paddled his boat across the lake and back
Romans were cultivating <fex>the land</fex> in Northern Gaul.
